    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>'Rats': No Accident</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Bruce Ornstein letter, commenting on Sept 13 article, says subliminal appearance of word 'rats' in political ad by Bush presidential campaign criticizing Vice Pres Al Gore's Medicare proposals was intentional, contrary to Bush's assertions</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Says Rats Reference in Ad Was Unintentional'' (news article, Sept. 13):</p>
        <p>A full-frame image of the word ''rats'' in capital letters cannot organically flash out of the word bureaucrats.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Bush Says Rats Reference in Ad Was Unintentional'' (news article, Sept. 13):</p>
        <p>A full-frame image of the word ''rats'' in capital letters cannot organically flash out of the word bureaucrats.</p>
        <p>Unquestionably, it was a separate edit that required careful attention to detail. In fact, it would take anywhere from 20 to 40 minutes to design, render and position one frame of the word ''rats'' in the body of a video message.</p>
        <p>I am not only insulted by this attempt to subliminally influence my voting decision, but I am also deeply offended by George W. Bush's feeble efforts to cover it up. Is this what he means when he says he will bring integrity and character back to the White House?</p>
        <p>BRUCE ORENSTEIN  Chicago, Sept. 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a video producer and editor.</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
